Our investigation was focused on summer because the heat stress becomes a health issue with hot weathers. The measurements were conducted at parks, squares, streets and commercial areas to cover wide participants during 13 days in July, August, and September 2021. The specific sites were selected based on landscape elements in order to cover diverse landscape characteristics, including spaces with tree, tree-lined street, waterside, building area, sunlit and pavilion (Fig. 1). The on-site measurements record air temperature (Ta
                        ), relative humidity (RH), wind speed (Va
                        ) and globe temperature (T

                           g
                        ) from about 9:00 am to 6:00 pm at 1 minute intervals. All measurements were performed during sunny conditions and partly cloudy skies, excluding rainy weathers. Automatic meteorological stations are installed at a height of 1.5 m from ground. Since the tripod does not allow the measurement of wind speed at a height of 10 m, the wind speed is measured at a height of 1.5 m. The instruments used for meteorological variables are Delta HD 32.3 and specific parameters are listed in Table 1
                        . All the instruments complied with the standard of ISO 7726 (ISO, 1998).

Male and female neutral UTCIs and unacceptable thresholds were calculated to explore the differences of the thermal sensation (Fig. 5
                        ). Line regression fitting was performed to identify the relationship of mean thermal sensation votes (MTSV) and UTCI. Neutral temperature is then calculated based on fitting formula. Neutral temperature of male and female was 26.6 °C and 27.0 °C, respectively, indicating the neutral temperature of males was slightly lower than females. The difference between the two slopes is not statistically significant (p > 0.05), indicating the response to temperature variation for females and males were similar. The NTR of female was narrow than male, especially in lower limit of range (Table 4
                        ). The regression lines of thermal unacceptable rates against the calculated UTCI were fitted for male and female to obtain TTR. The TTR of male was 16.8–33.6 °C, while female was 20.2–33.7 °C at 20% thermal unacceptability, revealing that female were more sensitive to low temperature. The heat acceptability of females was significantly lower than that of males when UTCI was higher than 33.9 °C.

To explore the effects of long-term thermal adaptation and psychological factors on thermal perception, we excluded the effect of thermal stress level. Two approaches are used for thermal stress classification: probit analysis and thermal acceptability approach. Probit analysis approach is based on the definition of ‘transition temperature’ (the temperature at which 50% of the subjects would change their thermal sensation votes) (Haghshenas et al., 2021). We determine the transition temperatures through the sigmoid response curves (Fig. 9
                        ). The intersection between TSV≥1 curve cross the 50% lines shows the transition from ‘neutral’ to ‘slightly warm’ which is occurring at 31.0 °C UTCI, TSV≥2 shows the transition points from ‘slightly warm’ to ‘hot’ at 38.4 °C UTCI, TSV≥2 from ‘hot’ to very hot’ at 41.1 °C UTCI. In addition, we divided heat stress levels as moderate heat stress, strong stress, very strong stress, and extreme stress corresponding to unacceptability rate of 40%, 60%, 80%, and >80%, respectively. Slight heat stress is lack in ‘Fiala’ model. We defined unacceptability rate of 15% as the lower limit of moderate heat stress. The classification types were moderate heat stress (32.4–36.6 °C), strong heat stress (36.6–38.9 °C), very strong heat stress 38.9–40.9 °C, and extreme heat stress (>40.9 °C). The two methods have similar classification results. Calibrated thermal stress classification in this study was compared with previous study (Table 5
                        ).
